1. Physicians are permitted to decide:
	1. Whether their practice is accepting new patients2; and
2. Which patients to accept into their practice.


	These decisions **must** be made in good faith and in accordance with this policy.
2. Physicians **must not** refuse to accept patients based on any of the prohibited grounds of discrimination set out in the Ontario *Human Rights Code.*3
3. Physicians **must not** refuse to accept a patient solely on the basis that the patient has:
	1. High, complex, or chronic health-care needs;
2. A history of prescribed opioids and/or psychotropic medication;4
3. Needs that require additional time to manage;
4. A physical or mental health condition or disability5 that may require the physician to prepare and provide additional documentation or reports; and/or
5. Beliefs or ideologies which do not align with the physician’s own and which may impact the patient’s therapeutic choices.6
4. Physicians are permitted to establish criteria for accepting new patients. These criteria **must**:
	1. Be directly relevant to the physician’s clinical competence, scope of practice, and/or focused practice area;7
2. Comply with the terms and conditions of the physician’s certificate of registration and associated practice restrictions, if applicable;
3. Be fair and promote equitable access to health-care services;
4. Be clearly communicated to prospective patients seeking care;8 and
5. Be shared with CPSO, on request.
5. Where physicians refuse to accept a patient, they **must**:
	1. Do so in good faith;
2. Clearly communicate the reasons for the refusal to the patient; and
3. Document the reasons for the refusal.
6. Physicians are permitted to prioritize patients with high or complex care needs, family members of current patients9, and those belonging to priority populations. Physicians **must** use their professional judgment to determine whether prioritizing patients is appropriate, taking into account the patient’s health-care needs and any known social factors that may influence the patient’s health outcomes (e.g., social determinants of health10).
7. Physicians may determine, on rare occasions, that they are unable to accept a patient into their practice after an intake appointment has taken place11. In these situations, physicians **must**: 
	1. Ensure that their reasons for refusing the patient are not discriminatory, in accordance with **Provisions 2-3** of this policy;
2. Inform patients, as soon as possible, that they have not been accepted into the practice;
3. Clearly communicate the reasons for the refusal to the patient, in accordance with **Provision 5b** of this policy; and
4. Document the reasons for the refusal, in accordance with **Provision 5c** of this policy.

